Insalutary: Not salutary or wholesome; unfavorable to health.
Inculcation: A teaching and impressing by frequent repetitions.
Innervate: To supply with nerves; as, the heart is innervated by pneumogastric and sympathetic branches.
Intuitivism: The doctrine that the ideas of right and wrong are intuitive.
Indemnification: The act or process of indemnifying, preserving, or securing against loss, damage, or penalty; reimbursement of loss, damage, or penalty; the state of being indemnified.
Illatively: By inference; as an illative; in an illative manner.
Improvement: The act of improving; advancement or growth; promotion in desirable qualities; progress toward what is better; melioration; as, the improvement of the mind, of land, roads, etc.
Insaturable: Not capable of being saturated or satisfied.
Insalubrious: Not salubrious or healthful; unwholesome; as, an insalubrious air or climate.
Impeccability: The quality of being impeccable; exemption from sin, error, or offense.

Imparipinnate: Pinnate with a single terminal leaflet.

Interorbital: Between the orbits; as, the interorbital septum.

Irrubrical: Contrary to the rubric; not rubrical.
Ignominiously: In an ignominious manner; disgracefully; shamefully; ingloriously.

itself: The neuter reflexive pronoun of It; as, the thing is good in itself; it stands by itself.

Infrascapular: Beneath the scapula, or shoulder blade; subscapular.
Irrecognition: A failure to recognize; absence of recognition.
Irregular: One who is not regular; especially, a soldier not in regular service.
Initially: In an initial or incipient manner or degree; at the beginning.
Infirmary: A hospital, or place where the infirm or sick are lodged and nursed gratuitously, or where out-patients are treated.
-ide: A suffix used to denote: (a) The nonmetallic, or negative, element or radical in a binary compound; as, oxide, sulphide, chloride. (b) A compound which is an anhydride; as, glycolide, phthalide. (c) Any one of a series of derivatives; as, indogenide, glucoside, etc.
Inopportune: Not opportune; inconvenient; unseasonable; as, an inopportune occurrence, remark, etc.

Ignatius bean: See Saint Ignatius's bean, under Saint.
Indusial: Of, pertaining to, or containing, the petrified cases of the larvæ of certain insects.
Intastable: Incapable of being tasted; tasteless; unsavory.

Insurmountability: The state or quality of being insurmountable.

Isodynamic: Of, pertaining to, having, or denoting, equality of force.

&Verbar;Impetigo: A cutaneous, pustular eruption, not attended with fever; usually, a kind of eczema with pustulation.

Atomic weight, 114.82.
Ism: A doctrine or theory; especially, a wild or visionary theory.
Imbursement: The act of imbursing, or the state of being imbursed.

Inexplicableness: A state of being inexplicable; inexplicability.

Inscrutability: The quality or state of being inscrutable; inscrutableness.
Isonicotinic: Pertaining to, or derived from, isonicotine.
Inweave: To weave in or together; to intermix or intertwine by weaving; to interlace.
Isospondylous: Of or pertaining to the Isospondyli; having the anterior vertebræ separate and normal.
Insusceptibility: Lack of susceptibility, or of capacity to feel or perceive.

iridium: A rare metallic element of atomic number 77, of the same group as platinum, which it much resembles, being silver-white and indifferent to most corrosive agents, but harder, more brittle, and with a higher melting temperature (2410° C, versus platinum 1772° C). Inwall: An inner wall; specifically (Metal.), the inner wall, or lining, of a blast furnace.
Inconceivability: The quality of being inconceivable; inconceivableness.

Induplicative: Having induplicate sepals or petals in æstivation.
Immobile: Incapable of being moved; immovable; fixed; stable.

Isabelline: Of an isabel or isabella color.

implicating: a charge that implicates someone (usually of wrongdoing).

Inductance: Capacity for induction; the coefficient of self-induction.

Immortelle: A plant with a conspicuous, dry, unwithering involucre, as the species of Antennaria, Helichrysum, Gomphrena, etc. See Everlasting.
Interscendent: Having exponents which are radical quantities; -- said of certain powers; as, x√2, or x√a.
Impecunious: Not having money; habitually without money; poor.
Infiltrate: To penetrate gradually; -- sometimes used reflexively.

It is attended with febrile symptoms, motor paralysis, and muscular atrophy, often producing permanent deformities. Called also acute anterior poliomyelitis, poliomyelitis and polio.  It is caused by any one of three polioviruses, and by the end of the twentieth century had been almost completely eradicated in developed countries by a widespread campaign of immunization.
Indian corn: A cereal plant of the genus Zea (Zea Mays), also simply called corn, used widely as a food; the maize, a native plant of America;
Indigestibility: The state or quality of being indigestible; indigestibleness.
Imitableness: The state or quality of being imitable; worthness of imitation.
&Verbar;Intransigentes: The extreme radicals; the party of the irreconcilables.
Indisputable: Not disputable; incontrovertible; too evident to admit of dispute.
Ichnology: The branch of science which treats of fossil footprints.
ice-clogged: having flow restricted by ice; -- of rivers or conduits; as, ice-clogged rivers.
Impossibility: The quality of being impossible; impracticability.
Intoxicant: That which intoxicates; an intoxicating agent; as, alcohol, opium, and laughing gas are intoxicants.

Incurability: The state of being incurable; irremediableness.
Infuneral: To inter with funeral rites; to bury.
Iriscope: A philosophical toy for exhibiting the prismatic tints by means of thin films.
Impaste: To knead; to make into paste; to concrete.
Incorporate: To unite in one body so as to make a part of it; to be mixed or blended; -- usually followed by with.
ilama: A tropical American tree (Annona diversifolia) grown in the southern U. S. having a whitish pink-tinged fruit.

Impasto: The thickness of the layer or body of pigment applied by the painter to his canvas with especial reference to the juxtaposition of different colors and tints in forming a harmonious whole.

in-situ: being in the original position; not having been moved or transferred to another location; as, an in-situ investigator.

Inisle: To form into an island; to surround.

internalization: learning (of values or attitudes etc.) that is incorporated within yourself.

Ichneumonidan: Of or pertaining to the Ichneumonidæ, or ichneumon flies.

Illustratively: By way of illustration or elucidation.
Infusory: One of the Infusoria; -- usually in the pl.
Imperturbable: Incapable of being disturbed or disconcerted; as, imperturbable gravity.

Intermine: To intersect or penetrate with mines.

Ilicic: Pertaining to, or derived from, the holly (Ilex), and allied plants; as, ilicic acid.
irresoluteness: the failure to behave in a resolute manner; fluctuation in intention.

immunogen: any substance that produces immunity when introduced into the body.
Incondite: Badly put together; inartificial; rude; unpolished; irregular.
Ilicin: The bitter principle of the holly.
Ipsus: a battle between the successors of Alexander the Great (301 BC); Lysimachus and Seleucus defeated Antigonus and Demetrius.
Inward: That which is inward or within; especially, in the plural, the inner parts or organs of the body; the viscera.
Icebird: An Arctic sea bird, as the Arctic fulmar.
Incombine: To be incapable of combining; to disagree; to differ.
India: A country in Southern Asia; the two peninsulas of Hither and Farther India; in a restricted sense, Hither India, or Hindostan.
Interlace: To unite, as by lacing together; to insert or interpose one thing within another; to intertwine; to interweave.
&Verbar;Incunabulum: A work of art or of human industry, of an early epoch; especially, a book printed before a. d. 1500.
Inland: Into, or towards, the interior, away from the coast.
Inefficacious: Not efficacious; not having power to produce the effect desired; inadequate; incompetent; inefficient; impotent.
imaginativeness: the capability of imagining; the power of imagination.

Infraorbital: Below the orbit; as, the infraorbital foramen; the infraorbital nerve.

&Verbar;Ianthina: Any gastropod of the genus Ianthina, of which various species are found living in mid ocean; -- called also purple shell, and violet snail.
Incredulously: In an incredulous manner; with incredulity.
ice-cold: as cold as ice; extremely cold.

Inevitability: Impossibility to be avoided or shunned; inevitableness.

Isabella grape: A favorite sweet American grape of a purple color. See Fox grape, under Fox.

Intentionality: The quality or state of being intentional; purpose; design.
interconnectedness: a state of being connected reciprocally.

Insobriety: Lack of sobriety, moderation, or calmness; intemperance; drunkenness.

Interknit: To knit together; to unite closely; to intertwine.
Intestinal: Of or pertaining to the intestines of an animal; as, the intestinal tube; intestinal digestion; intestinal enzymes.

Internal-combustion: Designating, or pertaining to, any engine (called an Internal-combustion engine) in which the heat or pressure energy necessary to produce motion is developed in the engine cylinder, as by the explosion of a gas, and not in a separate chamber, as in a steam-engine boiler. The gas used may be a fixed gas, or one derived from alcohol, ether, gasoline (petrol), naphtha, oil (petroleum), etc. There are three main classes: (1) gas engines proper, using fixed gases, as coal, blast-furnace, or producer gas; (2) engines using the vapor of a volatile fluid, as the typical gasoline (petrol) engine; (3) oil engines, using either an atomized spray or the vapor (produced by heat) of a comparatively heavy oil, as petroleum or kerosene. In all of these the gas is mixed with a definite amount of air, the charge is composed in the cylinder and is then exploded either by a flame of gas (flame ignition -- now little used), by a hot tube (tube ignition) or the like, by an electric spark (electric ignition, the usual method is gasoline engines, or by the heat of compression, as in the Diesel engine. Gas and oil engines are chiefly of the stationary type. Gasoline engines are largely used for automobile vehicles, boats, etc. Most internal-combustion engines use the Otto (four-stroke) cycle, though many use the two-stroke cycle. They are almost universally trunk engines and single-acting. Because of the intense heat produced by the frequent explosions, the cylinders must be cooled by a water jacket (water-cooled) or by air currents (air cooled) to give the maximum thermodynamic efficiency and to avoid excessive friction or seizing.

Invoke: To call on for aid or protection; to invite earnestly or solemnly; to summon; to address in prayer; to solicit or demand by invocation; to implore; as, to invoke the Supreme Being, or to invoke His and blessing.
Importunacy: The quality of being importunate; importunateness.
in-basket: a wood or metal receptacle placed on a desk to hold incoming material requiring attention, especially documents.
Interlacement: The act of interlacing, or the state of being interlaced; also, that which is interlaced.
Infandous: Too odious to be expressed or mentioned.
Inhabitance: The act of inhabiting, or the state of being inhabited; the condition of an inhabitant; residence; occupancy.
Implumed: Not plumed; without plumes or feathers; featherless.
Immortalization: The act of immortalizing, or state of being immortalized.
Interchange: To make an interchange; to alternate.
Imbitterment: The act of imbittering; bitter feeling; embitterment.
Isogonism: The quality of having similar sexual zooids or gonophores and dissimilar hydrants; -- said of certain hydroids.
Inadequacy: The quality or state of being inadequate or insufficient; defectiveness; insufficiency; inadequateness.
Isometric: Pertaining to, or characterized by, equality of measure.
imperialistic: Of, pertaining to, or advocating imperialism.
Immune: One who is immune; esp., a person who is immune from a disease by reason of previous affection with the disease or inoculation.
Irresolubleness: The state or quality of being irresoluble; insolubility.
Imminence: The condition or quality of being imminent; a threatening, as of something about to happen. The imminence of any danger or distress.
Insulator: One who, or that which, insulates.
Iodoquinine: A iodide of quinine obtained as a brown substance,. It is the base of herapathite. See Herapathite.
Iconism: The formation of a figure, representation, or semblance; a delineation or description.
Infertile: Not fertile; not productive; barren; sterile; unable to propagate its kind; as, an infertile soil; an infertile hybrid; -- of living things and of soil or land.
Inevitably: Without possibility of escape or evasion; unavoidably; certainly.
Inthrall: To reduce to bondage or servitude; to make a thrall, slave, vassal, or captive of; to enslave.
Immeasurableness: The state or quality of being immeasurable.
Istanbul: A city in European Turkey, built on the site of ancient Byzantium.  It is the former capital of the Turkish Empire, known as Constantinople before being captured by the Turks.
Intervary: To alter or vary between; to change.
Imprest: A kind of earnest money; loan; -- specifically, money advanced for some public service, as in enlistment.
Impress: The act of impressing or making.
Insanity: The state of being insane; unsoundness or derangement of mind; madness; lunacy.
&Verbar;Imprimis: In the first place; first in order.
Inferentially: By way of inference; using inference.
Insulite: An insulating material, usually some variety of compressed cellulose, made of sawdust, paper pulp, cotton waste, etc.
indigestibleness: the property of being difficult to digest.
Inductional: Pertaining to, or proceeding by, induction; inductive.
Isidorian: Pertaining, or ascribed, to Isidore; as, the Isidorian decretals, a spurious collection of decretals published in the ninth century.
Impressionless: Having the quality of not being impressed or affected; not susceptible.
Interrogatively: In the form of, or by means of, a question; in an interrogative manner.
Irvingite: The common designation of a member of a sect founded by the Rev. Edward Irving (about 1830), who call themselves the Catholic Apostolic Church. They are highly ritualistic in worship, have an elaborate hierarchy of apostles, prophets, etc., and look for the speedy coming of Christ.
Indispensableness: The state or quality of being indispensable, or absolutely necessary.
Interjoist: The space or interval between two joists.
Incapacious: Not capacious; narrow; small; weak or foolish; as, an incapacious soul.
Invalid: To make or render invalid or infirm.
Implication: The act of implicating, or the state of being implicated.
Intentiveness: Closeness of attention or application of mind; attentiveness.
Ineludible: Incapable of being eluded or evaded; unvoidable.
Imaginer: One who forms ideas or conceptions; one who contrives.
Indecent: Not decent; unfit to be seen or heard; offensive to modesty and delicacy; as, indecent language.
Inspiratory: Pertaining to, or aiding, inspiration; as, the inspiratory muscles.
Infralapsarian: Of or pertaining to the Infralapsarians, or to their doctrine.
Impoisonment: The act of poisoning or impoisoning.
Inframaxillary: Under the lower jaw; submaxillary; as, the inframaxillary nerve.
Inhold: To have inherent; to contain in itself; to possess.
Interventor: One who intervenes; a mediator; especially (Eccles. Hist.), a person designated by a church to reconcile parties, and unite them in the choice of officers.
Insurgence: A state of insurrection; an uprising; an insurrection.
Illaqueable: Capable of being insnared or entrapped.
Isoperimetrical: Having equal perimeters of circumferences; as, isoperimetrical figures or bodies.
Imbow: To make like a bow; to curve; to arch; to vault; to embow.
Ichthyophagy: The practice of eating, or living upon, fish.
Idiot: A man in private station, as distinguished from one holding a public office.
Interoceanic: Between oceans; connecting oceans; as, interoceanic communication; an interoceanic canal.
Insentient: Not sentient; not having perception, or the power of perception; devoid of feeling, consciousness and animation; inanimate; as, insentient stone.  Opposite of sentient.
Ill-looking: Having a bad look; threatening; ugly. See Note under Ill, adv.
Idiom: The syntactical or structural form peculiar to any language; the genius or cast of a language.
Incorporeality: The state or quality of being incorporeal or bodiless; immateriality; incorporealism.
Italic: An Italic letter, character, or type (see Italic, a., 2.); -- often in the plural; as, the Italics are the author's. Italic letters are used to distinguish words for emphasis, importance, antithesis, etc. Also, collectively, Italic letters.
Illacerable: Not lacerable; incapable of being torn or rent.
Insolvent: One who is insolvent; as insolvent debtor; -- in England, before 1861, especially applied to persons not traders.
indistinguishability: smilarity too close to be distinguished; exact sameness.
Interglobular: Between globules; -- applied esp. to certain small spaces, surrounded by minute globules, in dentine.
Interrogator: One who asks questions; a questioner.
Importance: The quality or state of being important; consequence; weight; moment; significance.
Induction motor: A type of alternating-current motor comprising two wound members, one stationary, called the stator, and the other rotating, called the rotor, these two members corresponding to a certain extent to the field and armature of a direct-current motor.
&Verbar;Insessor: One of the Insessores. The group includes most of the common singing birds.
Immaterialness: The state or quality of being immaterial; immateriality.
Intentioned: Having designs; -- chiefly used in composition; as, well-intentioned, having good designs; ill-intentioned, having ill designs.
Iconoclastic: Of or pertaining to the iconoclasts, or to image breaking.
Intercur: To intervene; to come or occur in the meantime.
Innovate: To introduce novelties or changes; -- sometimes with in or on.
&Verbar;Infusoria: One of the classes of Protozoa, including a large number of species, all of minute size.  Formerly, the term was applied to any microbe found in infusions of decaying organic material, but the term is now applied more specifically to one of the classes of the phylum Ciliophora, of ciliated protozoans.
Infringer: One who infringes or violates; a violator.
Ingravidation: The state of being pregnant or impregnated.
&Verbar;Idioplasma: That portion of the cell protoplasm which is the seat of all active changes, and which carries on the function of hereditary transmission; -- distinguished from the other portion, which is termed nutritive plasma. See Hygroplasm.
Immane: Very great; huge; vast; also, monstrous in character; inhuman; atrocious; fierce.
Inflorescence: A flowering; the putting forth and unfolding of blossoms.
Intussuscepted: Received into some other thing or part, as a sword into a sheath; invaginated.
Interlineal: Contained between lines; written or inserted between lines already written or printed; containing interlineations; as, an interlinear manuscript, translation, etc.
Irremediably: In a manner, or to a degree, that precludes remedy, cure, or correction.
Inefficient: Not efficient; not producing the effect intended or desired, or achieiving the effect by unnnecessary and excessive expenditure of resources; inefficacious; as, inefficient means or measures; inefficient methods are too expensive.
Inherit: To take or hold a possession, property, estate, or rights by inheritance.
Inexcusableness: The quality of being inexcusable; enormity beyond forgiveness.
&Verbar;Insessores: An order of birds, formerly established to include the perching birds, but now generally regarded as an artificial group.
Irreproachableness: The quality or state of being irreproachable; integrity; innocence.
Identism: The doctrine taught by Schelling, that matter and mind, and subject and object, are identical in the Absolute; -- called also the system of identity or doctrine of identity.
Infurcation: A forked expansion or divergence; a bifurcation; a branching.
Image: To represent or form an image of; as, the still lake imaged the shore; the mirror imaged her figure.
Imitative: A verb expressive of imitation or resemblance.
Inspectorial: Of or pertaining to an inspector or to inspection.
Inframarginal: Below the margin; submarginal; as, an inframarginal convolution of the brain.
Iron-gray: Of a gray color, somewhat resembling that of iron freshly broken.
Impendence: The state of impending; the state of being imminent and liable to happen soon; also, that which impends.
Iridic: Of or pertaining to iridium; -- said specifically of those compounds in which iridium has a relatively high valence.
Intractability: The quality of being intractable; intractableness.
Insufferably: In a manner or to a degree beyond endurance; intolerably; as, a blaze insufferably bright; a person insufferably proud.
Imprecate: To call down by prayer, as something hurtful or calamitous.
Incredulity: The state or quality of being incredulous; a withholding or refusal of belief; skepticism; unbelief; disbelief.
Icelandic: The language of the Icelanders. It is one of the Scandinavian group, and is more nearly allied to the Old Norse than any other language now spoken.
Impressible: Capable of being impressed; susceptible; sensitive.
Isostatic: Subjected to equal pressure from every side; being in hydrostatic equilibrium, as a body submerged in a liquid at rest; pertaining to, or characterized by, isostasy.
Immortality: The quality or state of being immortal; exemption from death and annihilation; unending existance; as, the immortality of the soul.
Infucate: To stain; to paint; to daub.
Imperative: The imperative mood; also, a verb in the imperative mood.
Ichthyoid: Somewhat like a fish; having some of the characteristics of fishes; -- said of some amphibians.
Interambulacral: Of or pertaining to the interambulacra.
Inordination: Deviation from custom, rule, or right; irregularity; inordinacy.
Insufferable: Incapable of being suffered, borne, or endured; insupportable; unendurable; intolerable; as, insufferable heat, cold, or pain; insufferable wrongs.
Idiomuscular: Applied to a semipermanent contraction of a muscle, produced by a mechanical irritant.
Irreversibility: The state or quality of being irreversible; irreversibleness.
invigilator: someone who watches examination candidates to prevent cheating.
Incircumscription: Condition or quality of being incircumscriptible or limitless.
Impest: To affict with pestilence; to infect, as with plague.
Illustration: The act of illustrating; the act of making clear and distinct; education; also, the state of being illustrated, or of being made clear and distinct.
Inclasp: To clasp within; to hold fast to; to embrace or encircle.
Inceration: The act of smearing or covering with wax.
Indwelling: Residence within, as in the heart.
Ischiorectal: Of or pertaining to the region between the rectum and ishial tuberosity.
&Verbar;Insabbatati: The Waldenses; -- so called from their peculiarly cut or marked sabots, or shoes.
Intersomnious: Between the times of sleeping; in an interval of wakefulness.
Irish: The natives or inhabitants of Ireland, esp. the Celtic natives or their descendants.
Instrumentalness: Usefulness or agency, as means to an end; instrumentality.
IHVH: A transliteration of the four constants forming the Hebrew tetragrammaton or “incommunicable name” of the Supreme Being, which in latter Jewish tradition is not pronounced save with the vowels of adonai or elohim, so that the true pronunciation is lost.
Incinerate: To burn to ashes; to consume by fire; to burn.
Invest: To make an investment; as, to invest in stocks; -- usually followed by in.
Incensement: Fury; rage; heat; exasperation; as, implacable incensement.
Instinctive: Of or pertaining to instinct; derived from, or prompted by, instinct; of the nature of instinct; determined by natural impulse or propensity; acting or produced without reasoning, deliberation, instruction, or experience; spontaneous.
Inhabitativeness: A tendency or propensity to permanent residence in a place or abode; love of home and country.
Impost: That which is imposed or levied; a tax, tribute, or duty; especially, a duty or tax laid by goverment on goods imported into a country.
Insphere: To place in, or as in, an orb a sphere.  Cf. Ensphere.
Inartificial: Not artificial; not made or elaborated by art; natural; simple; artless; as, an inartificial argument; an inartificial character.
Iambus: A foot consisting of a short syllable followed by a long one, as in ămāns, or of an unaccented syllable followed by an accented one, as invent; an iambic. See the Couplet under Iambic, n.
Insurable: Capable of being insured against loss, damage, death, etc.; proper to be insured.
Immolation: The act of immolating, or the state of being immolated, or sacrificed.
Incontestable: Not contestable; not to be disputed; that cannot be called in question or controverted; incontrovertible; indisputable; as, incontestable evidence, truth, or facts.
Issueless: Having no issue or progeny; childless.
Ill-bred: Badly educated or brought up; impolite; incivil; rude. See Note under Ill, adv.
Invisibleness: The quality or state of being invisible; invisibility.
Idolatry: The worship of idols, images, or anything which is not God; the worship of false gods.
Inspective: Engaged in inspection; inspecting; involving inspection.
Infallibleness: The state or quality of being infallible; infallibility.
Ironmongery: Hardware; a general name for all articles made of iron.
Informal: Not in the regular, usual, or established form; not according to official, conventional, prescribed, or customary forms or rules; irregular; hence, without ceremony; as, an informal writing, proceeding, or visit.
Illapsable: Incapable of slipping, or of error.
Indent: A cut or notch in the margin of anything, or a recess like a notch.
Irrevocable: Incapable of being recalled or revoked; unchangeable; irreversible; unalterable; as, an irrevocable promise or decree; irrevocable fate.
Irrejectable: That can not be rejected; irresistible.
-ing: A suffix used to from present participles; as, singing, playing.
Illeviable: Not leviable; incapable of being imposed, or collected.
Incloud: To envelop as in clouds; to darken; to obscure.
Inconsiderateness: The quality or state of being inconsiderate.
Inimicality: The state or quality of being inimical or hostile; hostility; unfriendliness.
Interpolated: Inserted in, or added to, the original; introduced; foisted in; changed by the insertion of new or spurious matter.
Inseparably: In an inseparable manner or condition; so as not to be separable.
Ignorant: A person untaught or uninformed; one unlettered or unskilled; an ignoramous.
Infraterritorial: Within the territory of a state.
Intertransverse: Between the transverse processes of the vertebræ.
Inquisitorial: Pertaining to inquisition; making rigorous and unfriendly inquiry; searching; as, inquisitorial power.
Ideologist: One who treats of ideas; one who theorizes or idealizes; one versed in the science of ideas, or who advocates the doctrines of ideology.
Invertin: An enzyme which causes cane sugar to take up a molecule of water and be converted into invert sugar.
Irremediableness: The state or quality of being irremediable.
Infanticide: One who commits the crime of infanticide; one who kills an infant.
Introducer: One who, or that which, introduces.
Impennate: Characterized by short wings covered with feathers resembling scales, as the penguins.
Ido: An artificial international language, selected by the “Delegation for the Adoption of an Auxillary International Language” (founded at Paris in 1901), made public in 1907, and subsequently greatly revised and extended by a permanent committee or “Academy.”   It is a revised and simplified form of Esperanto.  It combines systematically the advantages of previous schemes with a thoroughly logical word formation, and has neither accented constants nor arbitrarily coined pronominal words. For each idea that root is selected which is already most international, on the principle of the “greatest facility for the greatest number of people.” The word “Ido” means in the language itself “offspring.” The official name is: “Linguo Internaciona di la Delegitaro (Sistema Ido).”
Impuberal: Not having arrived at puberty; immature.
Immolate: To sacrifice; to offer in sacrifice; to kill, as a sacrificial victim.
Ide: Same as first Id, the fish.
Ineffability: The quality or state of being ineffable; ineffableness; unspeakableness.
Iroquois: A powerful and warlike confederacy of Indian tribes, formerly inhabiting Central New York and constituting most of the Five Nations. Also, any Indian of the Iroquois tribes.
Inventory: To make an inventory of; to make a list, catalogue, or schedule of; to insert or register in an account of goods; as, a merchant inventories his stock.
Insecable: Incapable of being divided by cutting; indivisible.
Incarnate: To form flesh; to granulate, as a wound.
Ineye: To ingraft, as a tree or plant, by the insertion of a bud or eye; to inoculate.
Inform: To take form; to become visible or manifest; to appear.
Intersectional: Pertaining to, or formed by, intersections.
Individuation: The act of individuating or state of being individuated; individualization.
Intern: To put for safe keeping in the interior of a place or country; to confine to one locality; as, to intern troops which have fled for refuge to a neutral country.
Inculcate: To teach and impress by frequent repetitions or admonitions; to urge on the mind; as, Christ inculcates on his followers humility.
Impalement: The act of impaling, or the state of being impaled.
Indecimable: Not decimable, or liable to be decimated; not liable to the payment of tithes.
Impoverish: To make poor; to reduce to poverty or indigence; as, misfortune and disease impoverish families.
Iodal: An oily liquid, CI3.CHO, analogous to chloral and bromal.
Indiscerpibility: The state or quality of being indiscerpible.
Impartation: The act of imparting, or the thing imparted.
Intercolumnar: Between columns or pillars; as, the intercolumnar fibers of Poupart's ligament; an intercolumnar statue.
Imposition: The act of imposing, laying on, affixing, enjoining, inflicting, obtruding, and the like.
Intransmissible: Not capable of being transmitted; as, an intransmissable illness.
incisiveness: keenness and forcefulnelss of thought or expression or intellect.
Investure: To clothe; to invest; to install.
Immeasurability: The quality of being immeasurable; immensurability.
Incogitativity: The quality of being incogitative; lack of thought or of the power of thinking.
internationalisation: the act of bringing something under international control.
Intaglio: A cutting or engraving; a figure cut into something, as a gem, so as to make a design depressed below the surface of the material; hence, anything so carved or impressed, as a gem, matrix, etc.; -- opposed to cameo. Also used adjectively.
Intercommunion: Mutual communion; as, an intercommunion of deities.
Itacism: Pronunciation of η (eta) as the modern Greeks pronounce it, that is, like e in the English word be. This was the pronunciation advocated by Reuchlin and his followers, in opposition to the etacism of Erasmus. See Etacism.
Isopogonous: Having the two webs equal in breadth; -- said of feathers.
Inductility: The quality or state of being inductile.
Imbricate: To lay in order, one lapping over another, so as to form an imbricated surface.
Inflect: To turn from a direct line or course; to bend; to incline, to deflect; to curve; to bow.
Incredible: Not credible; surpassing belief; too extraordinary and improbable to admit of belief; unlikely; marvelous; fabulous.
Instaure: To renew or renovate; to instaurate.
Inhumate: To inhume; to bury; to inter.
Importancy: Importance; significance; consequence; that which is important.
Incipient: Beginning to be, or to show itself; commencing; initial; as, the incipient stage of a fever; incipient light of day.
Interpale: To place pales between or among; to separate by pales.
&Verbar;Inoceramus: An extinct genus of large, fossil, bivalve shells, allied to the mussels. The genus is characteristic of the Cretaceous period.
ionophore: A compound that enhances transport of ions across cellular membranes, by binding them and carrying them across.  As a class ionophores tend to be lipophilic in nature; each compound is usually specific for one or a small number of ions.
Inharmoniousness: The quality of being inharmonious; lack of harmony; discord.
Interlucate: To let in light upon, as by cutting away branches.
Invader: One who invades; an assailant; an encroacher; an intruder.
Inboard: Inside the line of a vessel's bulwarks or hull; the opposite of outboard; as, an inboard engine; an inboard cargo; haul the boom inboard.
Irresolvable: Incapable of being resolved; not separable into component parts.
Inoxidize: To prevent or hinder oxidation, rust, or decay; as, inoxidizing oils or varnishes.
Iridectomy: The act or process of cutting out a portion of the iris in order to form an artificial pupil.
Integumation: That part of physiology which treats of the integuments of animals and plants.
Inexist: To exist within; to dwell within.
Indebted: Brought into debt; being under obligation; held to payment or requital; beholden.
Incontestability: The quality or state of being incontestable.
Impracticable: Not practicable; incapable of being performed, or accomplished by the means employed, or at command; impossible; as, an impracticable undertaking.
Io moth: A large and handsome American moth (Hyperchiria Io), having a large, bright-colored spot on each hind wing, resembling the spots on the tail of a peacock. The larva is covered with prickly hairs, which sting like nettles.
Inoxidizable: Incapable of being oxidized; as, gold and platinum are inoxidizable in the air.
Isagogics: That part of theological science directly preliminary to actual exegesis, or interpretation of the Scriptures.
Inconsequential: Not regularly following from the premises; hence, irrelevant; unimportant; of no consequence.
Incensor: A kindler of anger or enmity; an inciter.
Infrasternal: Below the sternum; as, the infrasternal depression, or pit of the stomach.
ill-formed: not grammatical; ungrammatical; not conforming to the rules of grammar or accepted usage.  Opposite of grammatical.
Idiophanous: Exhibiting interference figures without the aid of a polariscope, as certain crystals.
Inflexibility: The quality or state of being inflexible, or not capable of being bent or changed; unyielding stiffness; inflexibleness; rigidity; firmness of will or purpose; unbending pertinacity; steadfastness; resoluteness; unchangeableness; obstinacy.
Imbruement: The act of imbruing or state of being imbrued.
Impearl: To form into pearls, or into that which resembles pearls.
Intreasure: To lay up, as in a treasury; to hoard.
Innovation: The act of innovating; introduction of something new, in customs, rites, commercial products, etc.
Inconcludent: Not inferring a conclusion or consequence; not conclusive.
Insolubleness: The quality or state of being insoluble; insolubility.
Iridaceous: Pertaining to, or resembling, a large natural order of endogenous plants (Iridaceæ), which includes the genera Iris, Ixia, Crocus, Gladiolus, and many others.
Inevasible: Incapable of being evaded; inevitable; unavoidable.
imprinting: The learning of a behavioral pattern that occurs soon after birth or hatching in certain animals, in which a long-lasting response to an individual (such as a parent) or an object is rapidly acquired; it is particularly noted in the response of certain birds to the animal they first see after hatching, usually the parent, as in ducks who will follow the adult duck they first see.
Irrepealability: The quality or state of being irrepealable.
Invisibility: The state or quality of being invisible; also, that which is invisible.
Illuminative: Tending to illuminate or illustrate; throwing light; illustrative.
Izanami: The sister and consort of Izanami; mother of the islands and gods of Japan.
Intervener: One who intervenes; especially (Law), a person who assumes a part in a suit between others.
irritated: aroused to impatience or anger; as, made an irritated gesture.
Incorrigible: One who is incorrigible; a person whose persistent bad behavior cannot be changed; especially, a hardened criminal; as, the perpetual imprisonment of incorrigibles; incorrigible and disruptive children need to be placed in a separate classroom.
Inoculable: Capable of being inoculated; capable of communicating disease, or of being communicated, by inoculation.
Iatrochemist: A physician who explained or treated diseases upon chemical principles; one who practiced iatrochemistry.
Imagine: To form images or conceptions; to conceive; to devise.
Initiative: An introductory step or movement; an act which originates or begins.
&Verbar;Inion: The external occipital protuberance of the skull.
Indefinable: Incapable of being defined or described; inexplicable.
Inveiglement: The act of inveigling, or the state of being inveigled; that which inveigles; enticement; seduction.
Illegality: The quality or condition of being illegal; unlawfulness; as, the illegality of trespass or of false imprisonment; also, an illegal act.
&Verbar;Insectivora: An order of mammals which feed principally upon insects.
Isochronon: A clock that is designed to keep very accurate time.
Interpolable: That may be interpolated; suitable to be interpolated.
&Verbar;Isospondyli: An extensive order of fishes, including the salmons, herrings, and many allied forms.
ivorybill: A large, handsome, black-and-white North American woodpecker (Campephilus principalis), having a large, sharp, ivory-colored beak. Its general color is glossy black, with white secondaries, and a white dorsal stripe. The male has a large, scarlet crest. It is now rare, and found only in the Gulf States and Cuba.
Instauration: Restoration after decay, lapse, or dilapidation; renewal; repair; renovation; renaissance.
Imbathe: To bathe; to wash freely; to immerse.
Idio-: A combining form from the Greek 'i`dios, meaning private, personal, peculiar, distinct.
Insinuating: Winding, creeping, or flowing in, quietly or stealthily; suggesting; winning favor and confidence insensibly.
important-looking: appearing to be important; as, an important-looking sealed document.
Ineffervescible: Not capable or susceptible of effervescence.
Intinctivity: The lack of the quality of coloring or tingeing other bodies.
Ictodosauria: An order of extinct reptiles of the Upper Triassic.
Interferometer: An instrument for measuring small movements, distances, or displacements by means of the interference of two beams of light; -- formerly also called also refractometer, but that word now has a different meaning.
Intricate: To entangle; to involve; to make perplexing.
ill-fated: marked by or promising bad fortune; unsuccessful; as, an ill-fated business venture.
iron horse: A locomotive; -- an term no longer used.
Inc: A Japanese measure of length equal to about two and one twelfth yards.
Intuitionalist: One who holds the doctrine of intuitionalism.
Incorruptible: One of a religious sect which arose in Alexandria, in the reign of the Emperor Justinian, and which believed that the body of Christ was incorruptible, and that he suffered hunger, thirst, pain, only in appearance.
Inchworm: The larva of any geometrid moth. It progresses forward by first bringing the rear end of the body forward, forming a loop, then moving the front part of the body; called also measuring worm,  measuringworm, spanner, and looper.  See Geometrid.
Impinguation: The act of making fat, or the state of being fat or fattened.
Idalian: Of or pertaining to Idalium, a mountain city in Cyprus, or to Venus, to whom it was sacred.
Idiocrasy: Peculiarity of constitution; that temperament, or state of constitution, which is peculiar to a person; idiosyncrasy.
Invigilance: Lack of vigilance; neglect of watching; carelessness.
Import: Merchandise imported, or brought into a country from without its boundaries; -- generally in the plural, opposed to exports.
inositol: A white crystalline substance (C6H12O6) with a sweet taste, widely distributed in certain animal tissues and fluids, particularly in the muscles of the heart and lungs, and also in some plants, as in unripe pease, beans, potato sprouts, etc.  Although isomeric with dextrose, it has no carbonyl (aldehyde or ketone) group, and is therefore not a carbohydrate, but a derivative of cyclohexane.  Called also inosite, cyclohexitol, cyclohexanehexol, hexahydroxycyclohexane and phaseomannite.  There are nine possible steroisomers, not all of which are found naturally.  The predominate natural form is cis-1,2,3,5-trans-4,6-cyclohexanehexol, also called myo-inositol.  The naturally occurring phytic acid in plants is the hexaphosphate of inositol, from which inositol may be manufactured;  phytin is the calcium-magnesium salt of phytic acid. In solutions (as in water) ions are frequently bound non-covalently with the molecules of solvent, and in that case are said to be solvated. In Greek mythology, the beautiful daughter of Inachus, king of Argos, Greece, who was changed by Hera (Juno), in a fit of jealousy, into a white heifer, and placed under the watch of Argus of the hundred eyes.
   When Argus was killed by Hermes at the command of Zeus, the heifer was maddened by a terrible gadfly sent by Hera, and wandered about until she arrived in Egypt. There she recovered her original shape, and bore Epaphus to Zeus.  Epaphus became the ancestor of Ægyptus, Damaus, Cepheus, and Phineus.  She was identified by the Egyptians with Isis.  According to another legend, Io was carried off by Phoenician traders who landed in Argos. Intine: A transparent, extensible membrane of extreme tenuity, which forms the innermost coating of grains of pollen.
Inflater: One who, or that which, inflates; as, the inflaters of the stock exchange.
Ill-natured: Of habitual bad temper; having an unpleasant disposition; surly; disagreeable; cross; peevish; fractious; crabbed; -- of people; as, an ill-natured person; an ill-natured disagreeable old man.  Opposite of good-natured.
ill-gotten: obtained illegally or by improper means; as, ill-gotten gains.
Interepimeral: Between the epimeral plates of insects and crustaceans.
Imbecilitate: To weaken, as to the body or the mind; to enfeeble.
Incubate: To sit, as on eggs for hatching; to brood; to brood upon, or keep warm, as eggs, for the purpose of hatching.
Inclined: Having a leaning or tendency towards, or away from, a thing; disposed or moved by wish, desire, or judgment; as, a man inclined to virtue.
